Part 3

The shelter ran on a completely different kind of math. In the city head office, Vikram had spent his days watching ledger entries balance down to the single paisa. 

Here, a single sack of potatoes was expected to stretch for nine days, but occasionally it stretched for eleven because Ramu's nephew had brought three heads of cauliflower that had gone slightly soft at the edges and were given as a gift.

Vikram's job was the water. Every morning at five, before the trucks on the bypass started their high-pitched honking, he drew twelve buckets from the stone well.

The first six went to the kitchen for cooking. The next four went to the washing area behind the storage drums. The last two he kept near the drumstick trees for the children's morning wash.

His hands, which had gone soft from ten years of holding executive pens and checking ledgers, grew a thin, rough layer of yellow calluses along the base of his fingers.

"You are drawing that bucket too fast," Sarita told him one morning.

She was sitting on the brick steps of the verandah, using a piece of broken glass to scrape the dried mud off a pair of old rubber sandals.

"The rope will slip," she said.

"The rope is new," Vikram said, pulling the bucket over the iron pulley.

"Ropes don't care if they are new, Vikram," she said, without looking up. "They slip when they are tired."

She went back to the sandals. She looked tired herself, her cheeks having gone slightly hollow over the last two weeks, her eyes carrying the grey shadow that came when the medicine from the government hospital didn't suit her stomach.

She never mentioned her pain. But Vikram had started noticing the exact hour she went to her room to lie down. It was always three in the afternoon, when the heat of the tiled roof was the worst.

---

Ananya sat on the low wall of the well, her thin legs swinging over the side. She was holding a notebook Vikram had bought for her from the bypass store.

"What is this word?" she asked, pointing her pencil at the page.

"Equation," Vikram said, looking over her shoulder.

"What does it mean?"

"It means two sides have to be equal. What you put on the left must match what is on the right."

She thought for a moment, the tip of her pencil touching her lip. "Like a balance scale?"

"Yes."

"But if you put something on one side, and the other side has nothing, what happens then?"

"It tilts," Vikram said.

"Then it is not an equation."

"No."

She closed the notebook with a soft thud. "My school had a big blackboard. The teacher had three colors of chalk. Yellow, pink, and white. She only used the pink one when someone got the answer wrong."

"Which color did she use for you?"

"White," Ananya said, looking at the drumstick leaves. "I didn't get the answers wrong. I just had the bad blood."

She hopped off the wall. "Let's make the tea. Ramu's nephew brought the ginger today."

"What is your name?" Vikram asked, though he already knew.

"Ananya," she said, looking back briefly.

He had known another Ananya once. The name sat in his mouth for a second before he swallowed it back down and said nothing.

---

The tea stall near the bypass was run by a man named Shankar. He had one wooden bench that sat in the dusty shade of a large hoarding advertising cement.

Vikram and Ananya walked there in the evenings. It wasn't because the shelter tea wasn't enough; it was because Shankar's stall was the only place where the truck drivers and the local laborers sat together without asking who had what.

They sat on the wooden bench, their backs to the cement advertisement. Shankar served the tea in small glass tumblers.

Red tea. It was strong, sweet with local palm jaggery, smelling of the dry mud of the roadside and the diesel exhaust of the passing carriers.

"Your brother came to the factory yesterday," Shankar said, wiping a glass with a dirty rag.

Vikram looked at the road. A multi-axle truck carrying iron ore was moving slowly, its gears groaning under the weight.

"Reddy garu was with him," Shankar continued. "They had three cars. The big white one."

"Rohan likes the white one," Vikram said.

"People say he is very strict. He fined two loaders for being ten minutes late yesterday morning."

Vikram took a sip of his tea. The jaggery was burnt at the bottom, leaving a bitter, sweet crust on the edge of the glass. 

Ananya was watching a puppy playing near the tyre shop across the road.

"Let him be strict," Vikram said. "A new house needs a strong door."

"But you," Shankar said, looking at Vikram's faded cotton shirt. "You were the Ahuja saab. People used to stand up when your car passed the crossing."

"They still stand," Vikram said, smiling. "To cross the road."

Shankar laughed, a loud sound. He wiped the same glass a second time, which is what he did when something was on his mind.

"There was a Municipal Corporation jeep near your gate this morning," he said, not quite asking. "Early. Before the morning walkers."

Vikram looked at the road.

"The driver didn't stop," Shankar continued. "Just looked at the building, wrote something on a clipboard, and turned back toward the highway."

"It is nothing," Vikram said.

Shankar put the glass down. He didn't argue, which meant he wasn't sure.

---

They walked back to the shelter as the sun was setting behind the bypass hills. The sky had gone the color of a bruised plum.

Ananya was walking ahead of him, balancing herself on the concrete edge of the open drain.

"Vikram," she called.

"Yes?"

"When the school starts again, will you teach me the pink chalk words?"

"Yes," Vikram said.

"Even the ones that are wrong?"

"Especially those," Vikram said.

She smiled, her tight hair plates swinging as she ran a few steps ahead. 

At the shelter gate, the brick was still holding the iron grill open. The smell of Ramu's nephew's wood fire was coming from the kitchen—dry wood, slightly damp from the evening dew, mixing with the smell of the red tea they had left behind at the bypass.

He walked inside. The red tea was waiting.

